<subSubSection id="D9F16554FFB9BA15B705F673B6F0FE64" pageId="5" pageNumber="624" type="distribution">
<caption id="C5946657FFB9BA15B705F673B6F0FE64" inLine="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="624" targetBox="[870,874,1309,1334]" targetPageId="5">
<paragraph id="915436DFFFB9BA15B705F673B6F0FE64" blockId="5.[790,1383,275,702]" pageId="5" pageNumber="624">
<emphasis id="A39FEACDFFB9BA15B705F673B1E1FEFA" bold="true" box="[791,967,275,308]" pageId="5" pageNumber="624">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known originally from only type locality in S Andean 
<collectingCountry id="E9FC764FFFB9BA15B065F65AB69EFE95" box="[1143,1208,314,347]" name="Peru" pageId="5" pageNumber="624">Peru</collectingCountry>
but recently also found in a second locality in Santuario historico de Machu Picchu.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9F16554FFB9BA15B705F6D1B77DFC65" pageId="5" pageNumber="624" type="description">
<paragraph id="915436DFFFB9BA15B705F6D1B77DFC65" blockId="5.[790,1383,275,702]" lastBlockId="5.[177,1384,717,1334]" pageId="5" pageNumber="624">
<emphasis id="A39FEACDFFB9BA15B705F6D1B637FE1C" bold="true" box="[791,1041,433,466]" pageId="5" pageNumber="624">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 50-51 mm, tail 29-32 mm, ear 13-14 mm, hindfoot 
<quantity id="56139B3AFFB9BA15B70AF563B14DFDEE" box="[792,875,515,544]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="624" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
, forearm 33-8-34-8 mm (two specimens). Dorsal pelage of the Incan Little Mastff Bat is dark brown, with hairs whitish at bases. Ventral pelage is paler brown, with white on throat. Wings and ears are blackish brown. Ears are thin, have round tips, and almost meet each other on forehead. Tragus is small, with pointed tip, and antitragusis inconspicuous. Lips have slight vertical wrinkles and hairs. Gular gland is present on throat of males (no females have been captured). Dorsal profile of skull is arched, lacrimal and supraorbital ridges are slightly developed, and basisphenoid pits are poorly developed. I* is weakly developed, with slight trace of cingulum. Dental formulaisI11/2,C1/1,P 2/2, M 3/3 (x2) = 30.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9F16554FFB9BA15B4A0F4D5B18CFC1C" box="[178,938,949,978]" pageId="5" pageNumber="624" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="915436DFFFB9BA15B4A0F4D5B18CFC1C" blockId="5.[177,1384,717,1334]" box="[178,938,949,978]" pageId="5" pageNumber="624">
<emphasis id="A39FEACDFFB9BA15B4A0F4D5B304FC1C" bold="true" box="[178,290,949,978]" pageId="5" pageNumber="624">Habitat.</emphasis>
Montane forest at elevations of 1800-3000 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
